<br>
Most people just have no idea what something is worth, and a pretty good way to gauge interest is to ask people to make you an offer. If someone doesnt want to sell you something for the price you offer, tough luck, there is no need to come crying to the message boards. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukerryndarkwater.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kerryn Darkwater</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 346<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/28/01 6:44:28 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Greedy Fucks</span><hr size=1> I used to stand quite firmly against this but then I realized that this wasn't the the only way to judge a persons greed. Nor is it a true one.<br>
<br>
I had a few items to sell this weekend. One was a Velium Ruby Veil, the others were Bracers of Ro. The Velium Ruby Veil was simple. I know what Velium is worth. I know what a Ruby is worth and I know how difficult they are to make. <br>
<br>
But the Bracers of Ro? I didn't even know what these things were worth when I got them 20 levels ago. How in the hell am I going to now 12 months on? I've lost track of whats happened in EC with the prices since I stopped trading at level 30. Now I just run in when I need to buy something and run out when Im done. <br>
<br>
Quite simply I opened it for offers. First one came back as 167 pp for one bracer. Now I know that it takes a minimum of 100pp to buy each bar of platinum so the cost has to be higher then 200. But what about the effort that was put into it? Thy went eventually for 400pp each. I don't care what they worth. I was happy to sell them for that price and the guy I sold them to was happy to offer it.<br>
<br>
The economy in Norrath works different then the way it does on earth. You can buy a 7/31 Fine Steel Longsword for 5pp. But it'll cost you 700pp for a 7/32 Longsword of the Rare Mob. So stats aren't even remotely workable.<br>
<br>
Web sites with prices. No use either I'm afraid. Some guy goes into EC one day sees an item he wants and sells his Longsword of the Rare Mob for 200pp for a quick sale. If he enters this on to a web site he can devalue the item based on the amount of people who have posted before. If only one guy has posted the true price of 700pp he's effectively brought the price down from 700pp to 450pp and thats a big change.<br>
<br>
Conversely this works for a seller. All he has to do prior to selling an item is to head for all the price sites and ,under a false name, claim that he has bought the item for double its value. A few times of this and he can effectively bring the price up WAY above its true value. Its then very easy for him to sell it 3 days later when he says well on EQPrices a Longsword of the Rare Mob sells for 1500pp. I'll let you have this for 1000pp. Hes ripped someone off for 300pp and come out smelling of roses. <br>
<br>
Add to the fact that on many sites the price is worked out on an average across all servers its totally wrong. There could be one enchanter on Rathe capable of making Velium Ruby Veils. He can effectively charge 4 times its value and if he sells enough he can bump the value to whatever price he sets.<br>
<br>
Conclusion : Never ever trust a price site, especially if a person says &quot;go look on....&quot;<br>
<br>
So what can a person do to obtain a true item on a price. Well he can do a PC on...<br>
I'm sorry but I get quite sick of listening to people go through this conversation.<br>
<br>
Dood1 &quot;How much did you pay for the Longsword of the Rare Mob?&quot;<br>
Dood2 &quot;1000pp&quot;<br>
Dood1 &quot;Man you got ripped&quot;<br>
Dood2 &quot;Huh?&quot;<br>
Dood1 &quot;They're only worth 700pp&quot;<br>
Dood2 &quot;I did a price check, only guy that answered said 1000-1200pp so I thought I did O.K.&quot;<br>
<br>
You idiot. The seller did this.<br>
<br>
Seller1 tells Bestmate_01 &quot;Hey dude...can you do me a favour and shout 1000-1200pp please?&quot;<br>
Bestmate_01 tells Seller1 &quot;Sure dude...heh.&quot;<br>
<br>
Either that or you just got real unlucky. Either way I wont trust PCs whilst the trade is in motion.<br>
<br>
I used to buy low and sell higher when I was young at the game. Not much. Id make 200pp profit on a 1000pp item when I needed a little cash. I'd keep an eye out for prices and if I saw a Longsword of the Rare Mob going for 500pp for a quick sale Id grab it. Id then sell it for the 700pp it was worth. So if you ask me for a price check on a longsword of the rare mob im going to say this.<br>
<br>
500pp if you're buying 700pp if you're selling. Hey at least its accurate.<br>
<br>
Conclusion : Price checks are unreliable especially if a trade is in motion.<br>
<br>
So you have 1 choice left. You can sit round EC watching for this item to sell and asking how much its going for. You do this for a few days and if its not a very rare item you're quite likely to get a price. But your screwed if the item is rare that anyone rarely sees it. You're also screwed if you dont have that time to sit in EC.<br>
<br>
So until then you're always going to get &quot;Make an offer....&quot; <br>
<br>
I don't like it either. Some people use this for greed to further their own ends at the expense of others. It's unfortunately an open license to rip people off. But unless you show me a better way, proven to work...it's a way of life.<br>
